title: DJI INSPIRE 2 TOP MOUNT HANDLE FOR GROUND FILMING

description.text:
Update:

I added a new stiffer front top plate. If you are going to print in a more flexible material like PETG, ABS or alike i would consider using this version. Original is completely usable in these materials but i wanted it to be a little stiffer.

This handle is designed to be used with the DJI Inspire 2, allowing you to use the drone as a ground camera. This will allow you to carry the drone in an under slung fashion used by many when filming.

Everything fits well and attaches to the inspire 2 in areas that will not risk damage to sensitive equipment on board.

Use your slicer software to mirror the front and rear lowers as only one side file is provided for each. I found this to be easier than mirroring in the cad software as then i did not have control over position on the print bed.

additional hardware needed.

6-1/4 inch 1/4-20 threaded rod
(8) m3 x 20mm bolts
(8) m3 nuts
(2) 1/4 inch flat washer or can use lock was in addition to flat washers
(2) 1/4-20 wing nuts.
(1) rubber o-ring or heavy duty rubber band
(8) 3mm flat washers

single piece rear section can be printed in place of the 3 individual pieces. This requires a larger print bed.

assembly and installation video, be sure to watch the video to understand the best way to mount to the inspire. I updated the files for the front lowers so the nuts can be counter sunk and glued in place so it is much easier to assemble.

title: Printed WiFi - 3D Printed Wireless Connected Objects

description.text:
This is a collection of recent research out of the University of Washington about 100% printed WiFi sensors. A few videos have been circulating the internet lately, so I wanted to put together a set of information I was able to find about this research project. All of this research is still very new, but a very interesting concept. If you haven't heard of it already, I recommend watching these videos to get familiar with the concept:

  1. https://youtu.be/gU6-o9SIkMQ
  2. https://youtu.be/lD3lTtnoSOk

After you are familiar with the concept, I highly recommend:

  1. Viewing the PowerPoint presentation file titled: "Printed_Wifi.pps"
  2. Reviewing the Research Paper titled: "3D_Printing_Wireless_Connected_Objects.pdf"
    I've included both in this file set.

Additionally, the CAD files provided for this research were in the SCAD file format, so I converted them to STL for easier usage. These files are as follows:

  1. bowtie_antenna.stl
  2. coded_gears.stl
  3. dipole_antenna.stl
  4. flowmeter.stl
  5. publicDomainGearLib.stl
  6. publicDomainGearLibv2.stl
  7. rack.stl
  8. spring.stl
  9. switch_base.stl
  10. switch_contact.stl

Also, I've included the original SCAD files as well. Some notes about these parts:

  • Note 1: Part 4 - flowmeter.stl - This part will likely require supports when printing.

  • Note 2: Part 3 - dipole_antenna.stl and Part 9 - switch_base.stl - These pieces were printed partially with "Electrifi Conductive 3D Printing Filament" on the contact surfaces. See the images and research paper for more info about this process.

  • Note 3: To print the ferromagnetic segments of other models, they research team used "ProtoPasta Magnetic Iron PLA." See the research paper for more info about this process.

And while all of this is still not a 100% complete solution, the concepts and technical ideas have been pretty well described here. The models included here should at least let you test building a solution.

I’d like to give credit and my utmost respect for these designs to all the people that made this project possible. Credit for this work should go to the following people and entities:

  1. To the people that did the real work on this project:

    • Vikram Iyer (http://staff.washington.edu/vsiyer/),
    • Justin Chan (http://homes.cs.washington.edu/~jucha/), and
    • Shyam Gollakota (https://homes.cs.washington.edu/~gshyam/)
      THANK YOU for doing all this work, writing this research paper, providing all of this information, and building these SCAD files.

  2. To the University of Washington for hosting and supporting the Printed Wi-Fi project. The Printed Wi-Fi project site can be seen here: http://printedwifi.cs.washington.edu/. The University's Network and Mobile Systems lab page can be found here: http://netlab.cs.washington.edu/

  3. To Geoffrey L. Griffith (Me – GeoffreyG - http://www.thingiverse.com/GeoffreyG/designs) for Geoffrey’s converting the SCAD files to STLs and and uploading this project information to Thingiverse: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2715597

  4. And last, but most importantly, Thingiverse.com for being so incredibly amazingly AWESOME and hosting this unending repository of knowledge and product designs for the world to use 100% free of charge. Your contributions are the most important in this great endeavor and I’m eternally grateful for the services you provide!

description.text:
These are a set of snowflake ornaments I designed as a gift for my family. The geometric pattern they're all based on is called The Flower of Life.

For best results use the V2 of each snowflake with a layer height of 0.2mm, a 0.35mm extrusion width, and shell thickness of at least 0.7mm.

The older version I designed to print with a layer height of 0.2625mm only to discover that cura was over-riding the layer height to something that just happened to work right. However the chamfer on the top is a little too aggressive, causing some combinations of slicers, layer heights, and extrusion widths to result in "incomplete" top layers. I've fixed this in V2 to work well with 0.2mm layer height and 0.35 extrusion width.

I hope you enjoy making these for your loved ones.
Merry Xmas

  • Wiley Kyoto

My bad for being a little over zealous with the chamfers, resulting in a flat top surface only 0.2mm wide. I've been able to reproduce what you're referring to in cura by playing with the layer heights. Try the V2 of the snowflakes, they're optimized for 0.2 mm layer height and 0.35mm extrusion widths.

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Game Design by: Andrew Liaw MALU is an abstract strategy board game for 2 or 4 players. The objective of the game is to move both your pawns across the map to the other side of the board and exit the map. The first player to have both their pawns exit the map wins.
The mechanics of the game are simple enough that anyone can pick up and start playing, but the depth of skill and many possible strategies to employ, allows for seasoned players to truly be masters of MALU.
Each turn, a player must move their pawn and place a neutral tile onto the board. As you place your tiles, adjoining tiles create paths that your pawns can move along. As your pawn moves, you have the ability to pick up those tiles and reroute them to your advantage... either as a path to the other side or as a means to block your opponents. But be careful... if you get too close, your opponent can snatch those tiles away from you and use them for themselves! You can also place walls of ice and mountain peaks as obstacles or knock down walls for strategic advantages.
I have remixed 2 of dutchmogul's vikings into the player pawn for this game

description.text:
What better way to celebrate Winter than with your very own snowman? And if you happen to live in the South, like I do, you're probably better off printing your own than waiting for Mother Nature to deliver with the snow :)

Refer to the assembly guide photo for how each piece fits together. The pieces fit together snug enough to allow for assembly with or without glue.

Several Notes Regarding Assembly

  • Keep in mind that the eyes, buttons and mouth parts are not interchangeable and look quite similar. Care must be taken when printing to assure the correct part goes into it's matching hole.
  • Further, the eyes, buttons and mouth parts can only be inserted one way. You will have to rotate each piece until it lines up.
  • The upper set of 'pins_long' go all the way through hat_ribbon and hat_lower
  • The lower set of 'pins_long' go all the way through scarf_round
  • snowball_bottom is designed to just sit in the base. You can rotate the base to get the best look and then glue it in place if you choose.

description.text: So, as the title says, I made a Snowflake Christmas Ornament With a Space for Writing. Basically, this is snowflake (based off of this image: http://www.publicdomainpictures.net/pictures/140000/velka/blue-snowflake-99.jpg) that I made in OpenSCAD. It has a spot for writing whatever you want to write on a snowflake (Christmas 2017, or 18). I also used "Cura for Robo" (this was printed with a Robo3D C2), and I've included the GCODE file, which has the correct dimensions, but if you want to re-slice it, I've included the STL, and the print should be 100mm across (left to right). Actually, that's just how I did it, you could make it smaller bigger, just don't use the default size of the STL, It's too small. I've also included the OpenSCAD file, sorry if my code is a little messy, which brings me to why I'm remixing the Parametric Star by obijusn. At the top of the SCAD file, you can see the parametric star code, which I used for the star thing in the center. Anyways, I hope you like my model, thanks for stopping by.

description.text: Fully enclosed version of Geared Heart, Motorized Edition. Video of prototype at: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h-nVlsu_kVs&list=UUv_zm49u-RjnCJVwhUO-ecA Designed using Sketchup 8 and printed in PLA on a Makerbot Replicator 2 using Makerware 2.3.3.42 "Standard" settings.

Study "Assembly.skp". Obtain the following parts: 1) "6VDC 45 RPM Pinky Finger Sized Gear Motor 1" Long x 15/32" x 3/8"" from either amazon.com or directly from http://sciplus.com/p/MICROMOTOR_47952. Other sources are available, I've not tested them though. 2) Coaxial Power Jack - Radio Shack part number 274-1583. 3) 1.5 Vdc Power Supply - Radio Shack part number 273-315. I used the same emmett's heart parts that I used in Geared Heart, Motorized Edition (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:255280). "Emmett's Parts.stl" contains these (while it slices fine with Makerware 2.3.3.42, other slicers may have problems). The geared heart must spin freely on the center. If does not, pick a heart piece and insert one of the pins into the hole in that piece, then spin the piece while holding the pin. If the piece doesn't spin freely, remove the pin, make sure the inside of the hole is clean (e.g. no stray filament strands, I found quite a few) and and if not, clean it out with a modeling knife. Next, if still does not spin freely, slightly enlarge the hole using a modeling knife. Repeat this process for all heart pieces. The heart pieces should spin on their respective pins as easily as shown in this video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o8CkCe5A-1w. Print "Base.stl", "Gear Main.stl", "Gear Motor.stl", "Heart Center.stl" and "Top.stl". While printing "Top.stl", I paused the printer when the printer z position reached 4.2mm, then switched colors from black to red to match the red heart parts. Solder two wires (about 3" each in length) between the motor "+" and "-" terminals and the coaxial power jack. Slide the motor into the motor mount in "Base.stl", running the wires out the slot in the side of the motor mount, then mount the coaxial power jack in the hole in the back of "Base.stl". Press "Gear Motor.stl" onto the motor. Mount emmett's heart parts on "Center.stl". Slide the shaft on "Center.stl" through "Top.stl". Press "Gear Main.stl" onto the shaft of "Center.stl". Press the assembled top into the top of "Base.stl". Set the recommended power supply output voltage to 1.5vdc, then plug it into the coaxial power jack.

We've got a RED ONE Digital Cinema Camera at work and the RED ARM broke, and after multiple failed attempts at repairing it, I decided to design a new arm. "CAMS" stands for "Camera Accessory Mounting System" and this is the first piece, which is meant to mount an LCD Display to a RED Camera, but you can use it with anything that uses standard 1/4" mounting hardware. There's a bit more info in this blog post: http://rasterweb.net/raster/2014/03/05/a-new-arm-part-ii/

Print both blocks, six of the knobs, and one small knob, and add 1/4" bolts and nuts.

You can easily adjust the LCD Display tilting up & down, and rotating left & right, depending on how loose or tight you turn the knobs.

description.text:
This model was inspired by a print I made of the awesome Pangolin by amaochan. I was impressed by my printer's ability to deal with the very tight tolerances involved in that model.

I began with a two-cube prototype with an in-print hinge assembly. That's when I discovered the very similar design by austinvojta. Going by his narrative, he approached the design in exactly the same way as I did - make the radii of the cube edges match the swing of the hinge. This not only makes an awesome mechanism, is has a pleasant aesthetic in the hand.

The two-cube version is ideal if you want to test the hinge mechanism without wasting a huge amount of time - it only takes an hour to print. You can download the prototype here.

Onto specifics: the cubes are 0.3mm apart, the hinges are also 0.3mm from the cubes and 'float' in the spaces allocated to them. This model should be printed without support, but note that some fusing will occur. See Post-Printing on how to free up the cube.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus

Rafts:

No

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Material: PLA
Nozzle: 0.4mm
Speed: 45mm/s
Flow: 90%
Nozzle Temp: 200ºC
Bed Temp: 60ºC

Time to print: 4-5 hours.

Model pictured sliced using Cura.

Gently flex the hinges until you hear a crack - this is the hinge loosening from the cubes. Where a hinge looks fused to the cubes (particularly on the hinges that touch the bed) run a craft knife along the small seam between hinge and cube. This should free up the hinge. As you play with the toy, the hinges will loosen nicely.

Remember, this is an infinity cube - if the hinge won't budge in one direction, fold what is working back on itself and try again.

You may want to trim the edges that meet the bed with a craft knife to keep the smooth aesthetic.
This model was created in Sketchup using only the RoundCorners plugin. The rest was all arithmetic.
